entry.title: Remove CSS Zoom Adjustment for GetBoundingClientRect
entry.content:
This change modifies the behavior of the call for elements with a CSS

property. Previously, the dimensions of the bounding box returned by

GetBoundingClientRect were adjusted to the effective zoom of an

element, which is the combination of the page zoom and the CSS zoom.

This meant that the dimensions were not affected by either of those

values.



This had the unintended consequence of causing two elements with the

same size before zoom, but with different zoom properties, to have the

same sized bounding box, even though they had different sizes on the

page. This also caused crbug.com/967097



The new behavior adjusts the bounding box to the page's zoom, but not to

the CSS zoom. This means that two elements with the same size before

zoom, but with different zoom properties, will now have different sized

bounding boxes.



Follow up patches will add the same logic to other calls in the file to

ensure consistency between the calls.



Bug: 967097, 1510969, 1511048

entry.title: Lacros-Test: Remove outdated comment about WebAppControllerBrowserTest
entry.content:
WebAppControllerBrowserTest is the base test class used by

many web app tests, which include both ash and lacros test.

In ash, it only needs to run with Lacros disabled. If Lacros

is enabled and crosapi is also enabled (the tests runs in

lacros_chrome_browsertests), IsWebAppsCrosapiEnabled() should

be validated.



When I tested with LacrosWebAppsControllerBrowserTest in

lacros_chrome_browsertests, I noticed sometimes the test

(LacrosWebAppsControllerBrowserTest.AppList) failed with

VerifyNoAshBrowserWindowOpenRightNow() in InProcessBrowserTest::PostRunTestOnMainThread(), which means

there are some active ash browser UI not being closed after test

tears down ( probably race between uninstalling testing app and

removing it from ash shelf and closing the window).

So I added some clean up in the test tear down to close

all ash browser UIs.

entry.title: Adding a method to remove data between start and end time
entry.content:
There is currently no way to delete data between two timestamps on iOS.

All methods that remove data right now are either to delete all data or to delete data within the timeframe selected from the settings UI which maps to a `TimePeriod` enum.



This CL adds a method to the `BrowsingDataRemover` to delete data

between two timestamps. This method will be used for enterprise policies

that require to delete data only for a given timeframe. This will

mainly be used for policies that clear data from the time the user

signed in only.



An example of a policy that will use this in a follow-up CL is

IdleTimeoutActions which might clear data only for the time the user

was signed in if it was set as a user policy. Please see IdleTimeoutActions.yaml for more details about the policy.

button is visible). This will allow us to remove the extensions

controls view and add the toolbar buttons directly to the extensions

container.

entry.title: Move URT lookup backoff check to be after cache search
entry.content:
If a response is already cached, there is no need to fail the lookup due

to backoff mode. This CL also replaces two histograms with others due to

the changes.



This does not affect the backoff check for sampled requests, because

those requests do not check the cache.



Removed histograms:

- SafeBrowsing.RT.IsLookupServiceAvailable

- SafeBrowsing.RT.Backoff.State

New histograms:

- SafeBrowsing.RT.IsLookupServiceFound

- SafeBrowsing.RT.BackoffState



OBSOLETE_HISTOGRAM[SafeBrowsing.RT.IsLookupServiceAvailable]=Replaced with SafeBrowsing.RT.IsLookupServiceFound, which is no longer reports true when backoff mode is enabled.

OBSOLETE_HISTOGRAM[SafeBrowsing.RT.Backoff.State]=Replaced with SafeBrowsing.RT.BackoffState, which can be logged after a cache lookup

instead of always before.

entry.content:
build/util/version.py's WriteIfChanged didn't work as expected,

and always update the output file, even if contents is the same.

So, restat=1 doesn't work and always output file is considered

as dirty.



This is because st_mode includes file type bits, but mode

only includes permission bits.



Use stat.S_IMODE to compare permission bits with mode.

entry.title: Better test coverage for AutofillSyncMetadataTable
entry.content:
AutofillSyncMetadataTable is used to store sync metadata for all

components/autofill-related syncer::ModelTypes. The unit tests are

parameterized by ModelType. Since the list of relevant ModelTypes is

currently hardcoded, the tests are only run for two of the many

Autofill-related ModelTypes.



This CL runs the tests for all ModelTypes, by:

- Making the existing SupportsMetadataForModelType() public static.

- Using testing::ValuesIn() instead of testing::Values() and computing

the set of relevant ModelTypes as a function of

SupportsMetadataForModelType().



(Realistically speaking, since the logic is ModelType agnostic, it

doesn't really make a difference. But it's weird that the tests are

only run for two of the many types)

entry.title: Tweak NoStatePrefetch's pageVisibilityState
entry.content:
Before this CL, kHiddenButPainting is used in two cases:



1. to capture hidden tabs. These pages are treated as

a visible pages, such as media player.

2. NoStatePrefetch. This page lives in an invisible WebContents that

users are not aware of, so it should not be treated as a visible

page. It has a dedicated state because its previous version, legacy

prerender, needs to distinguish its frame's visible states from an

invisible frame. But now, we'd never render a NSP page, so it is

no longer needed.

(NSP is about to be replace by the new prerender2, but some

embedders are still relying on it.)



The case 2 is much closer to a kHidden page instead of a

kHiddenButPainting page, and should not be treated as a visible pages

as case 1.

So, this CL makes NSP use kHidden instead.



(Another option is to introduce another state, but after auditing all

callers, no one needs to know this state. Turing to "kHidden" also

allows us to remove the corresponding content/ public method.)



It also changes code that refers to this type, and turns to switch

instead of if to ensure they are aware of the exact types, in case

that we will introduce more states.

entry.title: Redistribute CSS properties between BoxData and SurroundData.
entry.content:
Struct fields for CSS properties are manually grouped into sub-structs,

with the hope that most property sets will touch just a few subgroups,

enabling efficient copy-on-write. However, this grouping is not

necessarily optimal and can be improved on using statistics. This patch

took the following approach:



1. Dump the Alexa1k test set (common top-level pages with DOM/style).

2. Compute style for every element, filtering out only properties that

fall into the ‚Äúbox‚Äù or ‚Äúsurround‚Äù groups (this yields about 336k

sets of property names).

3. Group identical sets of properties, and keep only the 100

most common sets (this accounts for roughly 61% of the cases).

4. Ask the Z3 SMT solver to divide those properties into two distinct

sets, such that the total amount of RAM used for those 100 cases

(weighted by frequency) is as small as possible.



This gave these new groups, with properties moved marked with an

asterisk:



Box: border-style*, border-width*, margin*, padding*,

min-width/-height, max-width/-height, width, height, z-index



Surround: border-image, border-color, border-radius,

left/right/top/bottom, vertical-align,

aspect-ratio*, contain-intrinsic-width/-height*



In other words, the primary effect is to move a fair number of common

properties from ‚Äúsurround‚Äù into ‚Äúbox‚Äù. (Surround is more than 300 bytes

large, so activating it less often is beneficial.) Some properties that

were never used, such as baseline-source, were just left alone since

they did not appear to make a large difference.



This gave a reasonable RAM improvement on our test set (measured by

the new BlinkStyleComputedStyleUsed metric; GCAllocated gives very

similar numbers):



Video 984 ‚Üí 912 kB ( -72 kB)

Extension 4024 ‚Üí 4031 kB ( +7 kB)

News 2074 ‚Üí 1983 kB ( -91 kB)

ECommerce 301 ‚Üí 269 kB ( -32 kB)

Social1 919 ‚Üí 878 kB ( -41 kB)

Social2 638 ‚Üí 637 kB ( -1 kB)

Encyclopedia 2144 ‚Üí 2009 kB (-135 kB)

Sports 676 ‚Üí 639 kB ( -37 kB)

Search 517 ‚Üí 489 kB ( -28 kB)



The box/surround groups where chosen for this experiment due preliminary

analysis of the same data set showing that they were frequently activated

together.



It is likely possible to improve on this algorithm with some sort of

clever clustering algorithm (in particular, the algorithm does not seem

to scale well to doing _all_ property groups). We tried some variations

like using top-250 instead of top-100 (which makes the SMT solver

incapable of running to optimality within a reasonable amount of time),

or using three groups instead of two (including one nested in the

other), without clear improvements.



Even though the algorithm optimizes for memory used and not number

of allocations (which would probably favor more skewed group sizes),

it seemingly also gets a small performance gain. Style perftest, Zen 3,

LTO but no PGO:
